ease's pathology. [Data: Entities (2076), Relationships (2352)]\n\n## Cognitive Disorder as a defining feature\n\nCognitive Disorder is a hallmark of Alzheimer's Disease, involving progressive difficulties in learning, language, and problem-solving. This feature significantly impacts the daily lives of patients and is a key factor in the disease's diagnosis and management. The relationship between Cognitive Disorder and Alzheimer's Disease highlights the cognitive decline that defines the condition. [Data: Entities (2077), Relationships (2353)]\n\n## Pre-Senile and Senile Types of Alzheimer's Disease\n\nPre-Senile Type Alzheimer's Disease occurs in individuals under 65, characterized by rapid progression and early onset of symptoms, while Senile Type occurs in individuals over 65, with slower progression and primary memory impairment. These classifications help in understanding the disease's variability and progression based on age. [Data: Entities (2078, 2079), Relationships (2355, 2356)]\n\n## Atypical/Mixed Type Alzheimer's Disease\n\nAtypical or Mixed Type Alzheimer's Disease presents with non-classical symptoms or overlaps with other forms of dementia, complicating diagnosis and treatment. This type highlights the complexity and variability of Alzheimer's Disease, making it challenging to manage and treat effectively. [Data: Entities (2080), Relationships (2357)]\n\n## Stages of Alzheimer's Disease\n\nAlzheimer's Disease progresses through early, middle, and late stages, each marked by increasing severity of symptoms. The early stage involves mild memory loss, the middle stage includes severe cognitive decline and psychiatric symptoms, and the late stage is characterized by severe dementia and complete dependence on caregivers. Understanding these stages is crucial for managing the disease and providing appropriate care. [Data: Entities (2081, 2082, 2083), Relationships (2358, 2359, 2360)]\n\n## Mild Cognitive Impairment as a precursor\n\nMild Cognitive Impairm